The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Mumbai, July 9 (PTI): A special riot court today sentenced former Shiv Sena member Madhukar Sarpotdar and two other party workers to one year imprisonment for inciting violence during the 1992-93 communal clashes in the city.           A fine of Rs 5,000 each was imposed on Sarpotdar, Ashok Shinde and Jaywant Parab.                   
	 Ranchi: At least 27 people died and 15 were seriously injured when a bus collided with a trailer on NH-33 near Palu village, about 25km from here, around 5pm on Wednesday. The driver of the truck was allegedly drunk.                   
	 Muzaffarnagar (PTI): Bharatiya Kisan Union leader Mahendra Singh Tikait has been charged with making casteist remarks against UP chief minister Mayawati, police said. This is the first case registered for casteist remarks about a chief minister.                   
	 Udhagamandalam (PTI): A private hospital was ransacked and the doctors and staff were assaulted by relatives of a seven-year-old boy, who allegedly died because of faulty treatment. Police said the boys family members were angered by the hospitals delay in informing them about his condition. The incident took place in the wee hours of Wednesday.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Delhi government will allot two acres for a Haj house, which will be built at a cost of Rs 35 crore, announced chief minister Sheila Dikshit. This Haj house will have medical facilities, a passport office, an information centre and a rest house. Air-conditioned buses will ferry Hajis to the airport from the house.                   
	 Panaji (PTI): Goa has decided to enact a special law that will enable its police to ask for detailed information from hoteliers about their guests. Director general of police S.Brar has said the law will debar fugitives from taking shelter in states hotels.
                                                                                                                         
